\n| footnotes          = \n}}\n\n'''Byron Mann''' ({{zh|c=\u6587\u5cf0|p=W\u00e9n F\u0113ng|j=Man4 Fung1}};) (born 13 August 1967), is a [[Hong Kong Americans|Hong Kong American]] actor of film and television. His roles include Wing Chau in ''[[The Big Short (film)|The Big Short]]'', Chang in ''[[Hell on Wheels (TV series)|Hell on Wheels]]'', [[Ryu (Street Fighter)|Ryu]] in ''[[Street Fighter (1994 film)|Street Fighter]]'', Silver Lion in ''[[The Man with the Iron Fists]]'', Admiral Nguyen in ''[[The Expanse (TV series)|The Expanse]]'', [[Great Ten#Accomplished Perfect Physician|Yao Fei]] in the first season of ''[[Arrow (TV series)|Arrow]]''<ref name=\"polygon\">{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/features/2014/3/10/5451014/street-fighter-the-movie-what-went-wrong|title=Street Fighter: The Movie \u2014 What went wrong &#124; Polygon|publisher=polygon.com|accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref> and Uncle Six in the [[Netflix]] series ''[[Wu Assassins]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://radiichina.com/actor-byron-mann-on-his-new-netflix-series-and-expanding-roles-for-asian-professionals-in-hollywood/|title=Actor Byron Mann on \u201cWu Assassins\u201d and Expanding Roles for Asian Professionals in Hollywood|last=Feola|first=Josh|work=Radii China|date=August 9, 2019|access-date=August 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nMann was born in [[British Hong Kong|Hong Kong]].<ref name=scmp/> Mann's father was a dentist. Mann's mother was Chinese-American. Mann grew up bilingual in English and Cantonese.<ref name=scmp/> Mann attended the [[Diocesan Boys' School]],<ref name=scmp>{{cite web|title=My life: Byron Mann |url=http://www.scmp.com/magazines/post-magazine/article/1162217/my-life-byron-mann|website=[[South China Morning Post]] |date=3 March 2013 |accessdate=8 August 2018}}</ref> an all-boys secondary school in Hong Kong, where he was active in community theatre as both an actor and a writer. After graduating, Mann moved to California.\n\n== Education ==\nMann received a degree in philosophy from [[UCLA]] in Los Angeles, California.<ref name=girl /> After college, Byron attended [[USC Law School]], but took a sabbatical after the first year. Back in Hong Kong, he received an acting role in the NBC Movie TV movie ''Last Flight Out''.<ref name=candi>{{cite web|title=Q&A: Byron Mann Of \"Hell on Wheels\" - Cowboys and Indians Magazine|url=http://www.cowboysindians.com/2015/08/qa-byron-mann-of-hell-on-wheels/|website=Cowboys and Indians Magazine|accessdate=7 May 2017|date=21 August 2015}}</ref> He returned to Los Angeles, graduated from USC Law, passed the California bar,<ref name=girl>{{cite web|last1=Service|first1=LUAINE LEE Tribune News|title=Actor Byron Mann owes his career to a former girlfriend|url=http://www.pressofatlanticcity.com/life/actor-byron-mann-owes-his-career-to-a-former-girlfriend/article_f3dd5712-d616-5e56-8090-acb7aba38582.html|website=Press of Atlantic City|accessdate=7 May 2017|language=en}}</ref> and pursued acting full-time.\n\n==Career==\nIn 1990, Mann's acting career began. Mann starred in films such as ''[[Red Corner]]'' and ''[[The Corruptor]]'',<ref>{{cite web|last1=says|first1=Toni Kanetzky|title=UNSTOPPABLE: Byron Mann Talks Career, \u2018Hell On Wheels\u2019 And \u2018The Big Short\u2019|url=http://www.iconvsicon.com/2015/12/17/unstoppable-byron-mann-talks-career-hell-on-wheels-and-the-big-short/|website=Icon vs. Icon|accessdate=7 May 2017|date=18 December 2015}}</ref> and in the television show ''[[Dark Angel (2000 TV series)|Dark Angel]],'' and has also co-starred in ''[[Catwoman (film)|Catwoman]]''<ref name=girl /> and ''[[Invincible (2001 TV film)|Invincible]].'' He is best known as [[Ryu (Street Fighter)|Ryu]] in ''[[Street Fighter (1994 film)|Street Fighter]]''<ref name=scmp /> (starring alongside [[Jean-Claude Van Damme]] and [[Ra\u00fal Juli\u00e1]]) and [[Koh (Crying Freeman)|Koh]] in the manga-based movie ''[[Crying Freeman (film)|Crying Freeman]]''. In 2012, Mann starred alongside [[Russell Crowe]] and [[Lucy Liu]] in ''[[The Man with the Iron Fists]]'', directed by [[RZA]], and presented by [[Quentin Tarantino]].<ref name=girl /> In 2015, Mann appeared in ''[[The Big Short (film)|The Big Short]]'', a [[Paramount Pictures]] feature film directed by [[Adam McKay]], alongside Brad Pitt, Christian Bale, Ryan Gosling and Steve Carell.<ref name=girl />  He also was a series regular on AMC's ''[[Hell on Wheels (TV series)|Hell on Wheels]]'', playing the powerful railroad mercenary Chang.<ref name=girl /><ref name=candi /> In 2018, Mann was a recurring character on Netflix's ''[[Altered Carbon (TV series)|Altered Carbon]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Petski|first1=Denise|title=Byron Mann Joins \u2018Altered Carbon\u2019; \u2018Pure Genius\u2019 Adds Alexis Krause|url=https://deadline.com/2016/11/pure-genius-alexis-krause-byron-mann-altered-carbon-1201852658/|website=Deadline|accessdate=7 May 2017|date=11 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nMann is interested in sports, especially tennis and golf. He was at one point a top-ranked tennis player, under 16 division, in Hong Kong.<ref name=scmp /> He is also a [[Chinese martial arts#Wushu|''wushu'']] practitioner, displaying his skills in a number of movies including ''Invincible'' and ''Street Fighter''.\n\nIn June 2018, it was announced that Mann was cast in the series regular role of Uncle Six on the [[Netflix]] series, ''[[Wu Assassins]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Otterson |first1=Joe |title=Netflix Orders Martial Arts Drama 'Wu Assassins,' Iko Uwais to Star |url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/netflix-martial-arts-series-wu-assassins-iko-uwais-1202862255/ |website=[[Variety Magazine]] |accessdate=July 27, 2018 |date=June 29, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n===Awards===\nIn 2016, Mann was nominated for the [[Golden Maple Award]] for Best Actor in a TV series broadcast in the U.S. for his role on ''[[Hell on Wheels (TV series)|Hell on Wheels]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Golden Maple Awards Nominees Unveiled|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/golden-maple-awards-nominees-unveiled-894363|website=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=12 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|1992\n|''Ghost Ship''\n|Charlie\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |1994\n|''[[Possessed by the Night]]''\n|Fok Ping Wong\n|\n|-\n|''[[Deadly Target]]''\n|Chang\n|\n|-\n|''[[Street Fighter (1994 film)|Street Fighter]]''\n|[[Ryu (Street Fighter)|Ryu]]\n|\n|-\n|1995\n|''[[Crying Freeman (film)|Crying Freeman]]''\n|Koh\n|\n|-\n|1997\n|''[[Red Corner]]''\n|Lin Dan\n|\n|-\n|1998\n|''[[American Dragons]]''\n|Shadow\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[The Corruptor]]''\n|Bobby Vu\n|\n|-\n|2003\n|''[[Belly of the Beast]]''\n|Sunti\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2004\n|''[[Catwoman (film)|Catwoman]]''\n|Wesley\n|\n|-\n|''[[Sniper 3]]''\n|Quan\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |2007\n|''[[Shanghai Kiss]]''\n|Jai Li\n|\n|-\n|''The Counting House''\n|Jackie\n|\n|-\n|''[[Blonde and Blonder]]''\n|Mr. Wong\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2009\n|''Motherland''\n|Michael Wong\n|\n|-\n|''[[A Dangerous Man]]''\n|The Colonel\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2012\n|''[[Cold War (2012 film)|Cold War]]''\n|Chan Bin\n|\n|-\n|''[[The Man with the Iron Fists]]''\n|Silver Lion\n|\n|-\n|2013\n|''[[A Stranger in Paradise]]''\n|Lek\n|\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[Rise of the Legend]]''\n|Black Crow\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |2015\n|''[[Absolution (2015 film)|Absolution]]''\n|Chi\n|\n|-\n|''Jasmine''\n|The Suspect\n|\n|-\n|''[[The Big Short (film)|The Big Short]]''\n|Wing Chau\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Skyscraper (2018 film)|Skyscraper]]''\n|Inspector Wu\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[Don't Let Go (2019 film)|Don't Let Go]]''\n|Det. Roger Lee\n|\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1990\n| ''Last Flight Out''\n| \n| TV film\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[Tequila and Bonetti]]''\n| Jeffrey Han\n| Episode: \"Brooklyn and the Beast\"\n|-\n| 1993\n| ''[[Murphy Brown]]''\n| Quan Chang\