ioners]]\n[[Category:USC Gould School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century Hong Kong male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century Hong Kong male actors]]\n", "name_user": "Cnwilliams", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:Sleeping Dogs\u2192Sleeping Dogs (video game)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Byron_Mann"}
{"title_page": "Gy\u016bdon", "text_new": "{{Cookbook|Gyudon}}\n{{refimprove|date=October 2007}}\n{{Italic title|reason=[[:Category:Japanese words and phrases]]}}\n{{Infobox prepared food\n| name             = ''Gy\u016bdon''\n| image            =Gyuu-don 001.jpg\n| caption          = ''Gy\u016bdon'' from a [[Yoshinoya]] restaurant\n| alternate_name   =beef bowl\n| country          = [[Japan]]\n| region           = \n| creator          =\n| course           = \n| served           =\n| main_ingredient  = [[rice]], [[beef]] and [[onion]]\n| variations       =\n| calories         =\n| other            =\n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''''Gy\u016bdon'''''|\u725b\u4e3c}}, literally \"beef bowl\", is a [[Cuisine of Japan|Japanese dish]] consisting of a bowl of [[rice]] topped with [[beef]] and [[onion]] simmered in a mildly sweet sauce flavored with [[dashi]] ([[Bonito|fish]] and [[Kelp|seaweed]] stock), [[soy sauce]] and [[mirin]] (sweet [[rice wine]])<ref>{{cite web |title=gyudon recipe |url=https://www.0-news.info/food/%e7%89%9b%e8%82%89%e9%a3%af/ |accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>. It sometimes also includes [[shirataki]] noodles, and is sometimes topped with a raw [[Egg (food)|egg]] or a soft poached egg ([[onsen tamago]]). A very popular food in Japan, it is commonly served with [[beni sh\u014dga]] (pickled ginger), [[shichimi]] (ground [[chili pepper]]), and a side dish of [[miso soup]]. ''Gy\u016b'' is the Chinese letter for cow, and ''don'' is short for ''[[donburi]]'', the Japanese word for \"bowl\".\n\n== History ==\n{{unreferenced section|date=June 2017}}\n[[File:Yoshinoya Kumamoto Japan.jpg|thumb|Yoshinoya in [[Kumamoto]] city]]\nDue to the [[Meiji Restoration]] and subsequent westernization, western customs like eating beef were adopted and spread throughout Japan.\n\nGy\u016bdon is considered to have come from [[Sukiyaki]]-don and the old dish gy\u016bnabe, where thin slices of beef are cooked with vegetables in a pot, and at some point was put over rice and served in a bowl.\n\nIn 1862, the [[Kant\u014d region]]'s version of gy\u016bnabe became the first popular version of this dish. In 1899 Eikichi Matsuda opened the first [[Yoshinoya]] restaurant, at the fish market in Tokyo's [[Nihonbashi]] district.\n\nFrom the [[Taish\u014d era]] (1912~) until the early [[Sh\u014dwa era]] (1926~), the use of cheap beef and the popularity of food sold from carts outdoors ([[yatai (retail)|yatai]]) in places like [[Asakusa]] boosted the popularity of the dish.\n\nAlthough traces of the traditional sukiyaki can be found in some gy\u016bdon containing ingredients such as [[konjac]], grilled tofu, and green onions, most major food chains serve it as beef with onion.\n\n== Fast food ==\n[[Image:MATSUYA FOODS in Japan 101.jpg|thumb|right|''\"[[Matsuya Foods Co.|Matsuya]]\"'' is a major gy\u016bdon chain in Japan. The restaurant opens round the clock ('24H').]]\n[[File:Foods ticket machine of Matsuya.jpg|thumb|Food ticket machine in ''Matsuya'']]\n\nGy\u016bdon can be found in many restaurants in Japan and some [[fast food]] chains specialize exclusively in the dish.  The largest gy\u016bdon chain in Japan is  [[Sukiya (restaurant chain)|Sukiya]]. Other large chains are [[Yoshinoya]] and [[Matsuya Foods Co.|Matsuya]]. [[Matsuya Foods Co.|Matsuya]] sells gy\u016bdon under the name ''gy\u016bmeshi'' (\u725b\u3081\u3057). Many of these chain shops open round the clock.\n\nSome gy\u016bdon chains charge for [[miso soup]], but many of them serve complimentary miso soup for customers who are eating in. The major gy\u016bdon restaurant chain that offers free miso soup is Matsuya, whereas other major chains like Sukiya offer it as a part of a set or combo.\n\n=== Customer specifications ===\n{{Original Research|section|date=May 2013}}\nThere are chains that allow customers to specify how their gy\u016bdon is served with code phrases like ''tsuyudaku'' (extra [[wikt:tsuyu|tsuyu]] broth) at no extra charge.  However, this service is only for people eating in confines of the restaurant.\n\n''Tsuyudaku'', in regards to gy\u016bdon, is jargon that refers to one kind of specification where the juice and tsuyu mixture is served in large amounts.  ''Tsuyunuki'' is where the amount of tsuyu is specified to be less than usual.  Also, the term ''tsuyudakudaku'' is code for a larger amount of tsuyu.\n\nSometimes, as with ''tsuyudakudakudaku'' (\"dripping with soupiness\"), people will request that the daku, or amount of tsuyu, be exceedingly increased.\n\nThere's a theory that says '''daku''' comes from the '''taku''' part of ''takusan'' (eng: many / a lot) which, when doubled as in ''daku-daku'', is also the [[onomatopoeia]] (imitative word) for the sound of dripping.\n\nThe origin of tsuyudaku comes from Japanese businessmen ([[salaryman]]) on their morning commute to work who, due to time restrictions, ask for extra soupy gy\u016bdon (''gy\u016bdon tsuyu ome ni'') so that they can eat it quickly.  \n\nThis trend became so common, that the term ''tsuyudaku'' quickly spread among proprietors of popular gy\u016bdon chains.\n\n== Beef ban ==\n[[File:Sukiya Glow (38266162006).jpg|thumb|[[Sukiya (restaurant chain)|Sukiya]]]]\nAs a consequence of the fear of [[Bovine spongiform encephalopathy|mad cow disease]] and a ban on imports of beef from the [[United States]], Yoshinoya and most competitors were forced to terminate gy\u016bdon sales in [[Japan]] on February 11, 2004. [[Yoshinoya]] moved its business to a similar dish made with pork instead of beef, which it named ''[[butadon]]'' (\u8c5a\u4e3c). [[Sukiya (restaurant chain)|Sukiya]] continued to serve gy\u016bdon (using [[Australia]]n beef) and also added a dish, ''tondon'', equivalent to Yoshinoya's ''butadon'', to its menu. (''Buta'' and ''ton'' are both Japanese words for ''pig'' or ''pork'', written with the same [[kanji|Han character]], \u8c5a. See [[tonkatsu]], [[tonjiru]].)\n\nThe [[Diet of Japan|Japanese Diet]] voted to resume beef imports from the United States in early May 2005, but the ban was reinstated in January 2006 after detectable quantities of prohibited spine tissue were found in the first post-ban shipments arriving in Japan. As the issue was discussed between the United States and Japanese governments, gy\u016bdon vendors and customers waited for a resolution. As of September 2006, the ban has been lifted.<ref>As reported by MediaCorp. (''[http://www.todayonline.com/articles/143251.asp Fans celebrate return of Yoshinoya beef bowl after lifting of US beef ban]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}'')</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Donburi]]\n*[[Katsudon]]\n*[[Oyakodon]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Gy\u016bdon}}\n* [https://archive.is/20130210132622/http://kitchen-ninja.blog.de/2011/04/13/food-print-24-gy-363-don-10998353/ Everyday Japanese Cooking]\n{{Beef}}\n{{Rice dishes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gyudon}}\n[[Category:Donburi]]\n[[Category:Japanese cuisine]]\n[[Category:Japanese rice dishes]]\n", "text_old": "{{Cookbook|Gyudon}}\n{{refimprove|date=October 2007}}\n{{Italic title|reason=[[:Category:Japanese words and phrases]]}}\n{{Infobox prepared food\n| name             = ''Gy\u016bdon''\n| image            =Gyuu-don 001.jpg\n| caption          = ''Gy\u016bdon'' from a [[Yoshinoya]] restaurant\n| alternate_name   =beef bowl\n| country          = [[Japan]]\n| region           = \n| creator          =\n| course           = \n| served           =\n| main_ingredient  = [[rice]], [[beef]] and [[onion]]\n| variations       =\n| calories         =\n| other            =\n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''''Gy\u016bdon'''''|\u725b\u4e3c}}, literally \"beef bowl\", is a [[Cuisine of Japan|Japanese dish]] consisting of a bowl of [[rice]] topped with [[beef]] and [[onion]] simmered in a mildly sweet sauce flavored with [[dashi]] ([[Bonito|fish]] and [[Kelp|seaweed]] stock), [[soy sauce]] and [[mirin]] (sweet [[rice wine]]). It sometimes also includes [[shirataki]] noodles, and is sometimes topped with a raw [[Egg (food)|egg]] or a soft poached egg ([[onsen tamago]]). A very popular food in Japan, it is commonly served with [[beni sh\u014dga]] (pickled ginger), [[shichimi]] (ground [[chili pepper]]), and a side dish of [[miso soup]]. ''Gy\u016b'' is the Chinese letter for cow, and ''don'' is short for ''[[donburi]]'', the Japanese word for \"bowl\".\n\n== History ==\n{{unreferenced section|date=June 2017}}\n[[File:Yoshinoya Kumamoto Japan.jpg|thumb|Yoshinoya in [[Kumamoto]] city]]\nDue to the [[Meiji Restoration]] and subsequent westernization, western customs like eating beef were adopted and spread throughout Japan.\n\nGy\u016bdon is considered to have come from [[Sukiyaki]]-don and the old dish gy\u016bnabe, where thin slices of beef are cooked with vegetables in a pot, and at some point was put over rice and served in a bowl.\n\nIn 1862, the [[Kant\u014d region]]'s version of gy\u016bnabe became the first popular version of this dish. In 1899 Eikichi Matsuda opened the first [[Yoshinoya]] restaurant, at the fish market in Tokyo's [[Nihonbashi]] district.\n\nFrom the [[Taish\u014d era]] (1912~) until the early [[Sh\u014dwa era]] (1926~), the use of cheap beef and the popularity of food sold from carts outdoors ([[yatai (retail)|yatai]]) in places like [[Asakusa]] boosted the popularity of the dish.\n\nAlthough traces of the traditional sukiyaki can be found in some gy\u016bdon containing ingredients such as [[konjac]], grilled tofu, and green onions, most major food chains serve it as beef with onion.\n\n== Fast food ==\n[[Image:MATSUYA FOODS in Japan 101.jpg|thumb|right|''\"[[Matsuya Foods Co.|Matsuya]]\"'' is a major gy\u016bdon chain in Japan. The restaurant opens round the clock ('24H').]]\n[[File:Foods ticket machine of Matsuya.jpg|thumb|Food ticket machine in ''Matsuya'']]\n\nGy\u016bdon can be found in many restaurants in Japan and some [[fast food]] chains specialize exclusively in the dish.  The largest gy\u016bdon chain in Japan is  [[Sukiya (restaurant chain)|Sukiya]]. Other large chains are [[Yoshinoya]] and [[Matsuya Foods Co.|Matsuya]]. [[Matsuya Foods Co.|Matsuya]] sells gy\u016bdon under the name ''gy\u016bmeshi'' (\u725b\u3081\u3057). Many of these chain shops open round the clock.\n\nSome gy\u016bdon chains charge for [[miso soup]], but many of them serve complimentary miso soup for customers who are eating in. The major gy\u016bdon restaurant chain that offers free miso soup is Matsuya, whereas other major chains like Sukiya offer it as a part of a set or combo.\n\n=== Customer specifications ===\n{{Original Research|section|date=May 2013}}\nThere are chains that allow customers to specify how their gy\u016bdon is served with code phrases like ''tsuyudaku'' (extra [[wikt:tsuyu|tsuyu]] broth) at no extra charge.  However, this service is only for people eating in confines of the restaurant.\n\n''Tsuyudaku'', in regards to gy\u016bdon, is jargon that refers to one kind of specification where the juice and tsuyu mixture is served in large amounts.  ''Tsuyunuki'' is where the amount of tsuyu is specified to be less than usual.  Also, the term ''tsuyudakudaku'' is code for a larger amount of tsuyu.\n\nSometimes, as with ''tsuyudakudakudaku'' (\"dripping with soupiness\"), people will request that the daku, or amount of tsuyu, be exceedingly increased.\n\nThere's a theory that says '''daku''' comes from the '''taku''' part of ''takusan'' (eng: many / a lot) which, when doubled as in ''daku-daku'', is also the [[onomatopoeia]] (imitative word) for the sound of dripping.\n\nThe origin of tsuyudaku comes from Japanese businessmen ([[salaryman]]) on their morning commute to work who, due to time restrictions, ask for extra soupy gy\u016bdon (''gy\u016bdon tsuyu ome ni'') so that they can eat it quickly.  \n\nThis trend became so common, that the term ''tsuyudaku'' quickly spread among proprietors of popular gy\u016bdon chains.\n\n== Beef ban ==\n[[File:Sukiya Glow (38266162006).jpg|thumb|[[Sukiya (restaurant chain)|Sukiya]]]]\nAs a consequence of the fear of [[Bovine spongiform encephalopathy|mad cow disease]] and a ban on imports of beef from the [[United States]], Yoshinoya and most competitors were forced to terminate gy\u016bdon sales in [[Japan]] on February 11, 2004. [[Yoshinoya]] moved its business to a similar dish made with pork instead of beef, which it named ''[[butadon]]'' (\u8c5a\u4e3c). [[Sukiya (restaurant chain)|Sukiya]] continued to serve gy\u016bdon (using [[Australia]]n beef) and also added a dish, ''tondon'', equivalent to Yoshinoya's ''butadon'', to its menu. (''Buta'' and ''ton'' are both Japanese words for ''pig'' or ''pork'', written with the same [[kanji|Han character]], \u8c5a. See [[tonkatsu]], [[tonjiru]].)\n\nThe [[Diet of Japan|Japanese Diet]] voted to resume beef imports from the United States in early May 2005, but the ban was reinstated in January 2006 after detectable quantities of prohibited spine tissue were found in the first post-ban shipments arriving in Japan. As the issue was discussed between the United States and Japanese governments, gy\u016bdon vendors and customers waited for a resolution. As of September 2006, the ban has been lifted.<ref>As reported by MediaCorp. (''[http://www.todayonline.com/articles/143251.asp Fans celebrate return of Yoshinoya beef bowl after lifting of US beef ban]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}'')</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Donburi]]\n*[[Katsudon]]\n*[[Oyakodon]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Gy\u016bdon}}\n* [https://archive.is/20130210132622/http://kitchen-ninja.blog.de/2011/04/13/food-print-24-gy-363-don-10998353/ Everyday Japanese Cooking]\n{{Beef}}\n{{Rice dishes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gyudon}}\n[[Category:Donburi]]\n[[Category:Japanese cuisine]]\n[[Category:Japanese rice dishes]]\n", "name_user": "Qin096", "label": "safe", "comment": "add gyudon recipe to first section", "url_page"